        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Imaging requirements: We will observe the 3-mm dust continuum emission and C18O(1-0) line emission towards G11.36. We require an angular resolution of 3"; This gives 0.048 pc at the cloud distance, which resolves the typical diameter of 
dense cores/protostellar envelopes (~0.1 pc). 

Requested sensitivity (continuum): In order to combine ALMA data with dust extinction data that will be used to recover large spatial scales, the dynamic ranges of the data need to overlap. The extinction technique recovers most reliably the column density range 10-20 x 10^21 cm-2. Therefore, we need the ALMA data to reach about ~10 x 10^21 cm-2. Assuming Ossenkopf &amp; Henning (1994) dust properties for moderately coagulated dust grains with thin ice mantles, beta index of 2, temperature of 15 K, and requiring 3-sigma detections, this translates to the rms sensitivity of ~0.50 mJy. Accounting for about 80 % flux losses due to spatial filtering, we arrive to the required sensitivity of ~0.10 mJy. The ALMA OT then gives about 30 s integration time per mosaic point to reach this sensitivity.

Requested sensitivity (C18O): Our science goal sets that we want to detect typical isolated thermal equilibrium filaments, if they are present in the cloud. Earlier works, and particularly that of Hacar et al. (2013, A&amp;A, 554, A55) whose analysis we will follow, have shown that C18O emission from the filaments is typically on the level of at least 2-3 K / 50" beam. This translates to ~67 Jy / 50" beam, and further, to 0.31 Jy / 3.4" beam. Assuming a beam filling factor of about 5 from the 50” beam (massive filament is expected to have a strong column density contrast, enhancing this factor), and a flux loss of ~50% due to missing spatial frequencies, we are left with ~770 mJy / beam. If we require S/N ratio of 10, we arrive to the 1-sigma rms requirement of ~80 mJy. Based on the Sensitivity Calculator, this noise level is reached in about 12 s. Thus, the total time-on-target is rather set by the continuum observations that require about 30 s integration time. This also somewhat improves the S/N of C18O observations.

Correlator setup: For the C18O(1-0) observations at 109.782 GHz, we propose to 
employ the frequency division correlator mode (FDM) that provides dual 
polarisation and 58.594 MHz bandwidth split into 3840 channels. This setting 
results in a channel spacing of 15.259 kHz or velocity resolution of 0.083 km/s 
(Hanning smoothed value). The C18O(1-0) line is placed in the USB of Band 3. 
The remaining three basebands (two in the LSB, one in the USB) are reserved for 
the 3-mm continuum observations. For the latter basebands, the Time Division 
Mode (TDM) with a 2-GHz wide band is used.

</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
