    <prp:abstract>Massive filamentary clouds are thought to play a central role in controlling the formation of high-mass stars and star-clusters. Hampering this picture, we do not know what processes govern the fragmentation of massive filaments, and hence, their star formation. This is because we do not have observational census of how fragmentation proceeds during the filament evolution. We propose making progress by utilizing ALMA to measure the fragmentation modes of two filaments that are in distinctively different stages of their evolution. One is an evolved filament that has formed protostars along its entire length. Another is a less evolved filament without clear sings of star formation.  We will observe 110 GHz continuum and C18O line emission. These data, together with our high-dynamic-range dust extinction data, are used to describe the hierarchy of fragmentation from five parsecs scale down to the Jeans’ length in the clouds. Comparison of the fragmentation modes of the two clouds directly defines the evolution of fragmentation as a function of evolutionary stage.</prp:abstract>
